The unusual intra-atrial course of the right-sided SVC was discovered at surgery. Retrospective analysis and reconstruction of the preoperative cardiac CT scan did, in fact, allow us to visualize this abnormal course (Figure 3
). Although the exact anatomy of the right-sided atrial appendage was not definitively determined, as there were numerous adhesions as a result of the first operation, it seems very likely that the anatomic diagnosis is heterotaxy syndrome of the left isomerism type. As a matter of fact, interrupted IVC with azygos continuation to a left SVC, polysplenia, partial AV canal defect with common atrium, and median location of the liver are all consistent with this anatomic diagnosis. However, the unusual anatomy of the right-sided SVC and its low opening in the atrium has not been described, even in a large study of venoatrial connections in 183 cases of visceroatrial heterotaxy with congenital heart disease including 58 cases with left isomerism.
